"{\"uid\": \"si.com-golf-olympic-qualifying-questioned-years-strife-land-paris\", \"text\": \"SAINT QUENTIN-EN-YVELINES, France \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s professional golf has endured its share of controversy over the past two years and so it is only fitting that some of the same laments would surface at the Olympic Golf Tournament.  And given that the Olympic Games themselves are seemingly always rife with some sort of strife, it makes sense that such concerns would also drift away from the Paris Olympic Village out to the golf venue near Versailles.  It is the qualification system for the 60-man field that has come under scrutiny this week, borne of course out of the emergence of the LIV Golf League and its lack of accreditation by the Official World Golf Ranking.  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the same system that determines who competes in the Olympic golf event that begins Thursday at Le Golf National. (Click here for tee times.)  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just the situation in golf right now, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s unfair,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d said Carlos Ortiz, who is representing Mexico along with Abraham Ancer. Both play for LIV Golf. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEspecially Olympic Games, you want to have the best golfers right here, but politics somehow manage things still.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI still feel there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s golfers that should be here and couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be here because of what has happened. I think the Olympic Games definitely should be neutral. They should have not turned away ranking players accordingly, especially now that the World Ranking points don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t really work anymore.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a lot to unpack there, so let\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s dig in.  >Back in 2009, when golf\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s leaders were pitching the sport to be included in the Games, there were no guarantees. At an October 2009 meeting, the International Golf Federation brought Padraig Harrington, Michelle Wie and Suzann Pettersen to Copenhagen for a final pitch and had videotaped messages from Tiger Woods and Ernie Els, who were playing in the Presidents Cup that week in San Francisco.  The IGF wanted the International Olympic Committee to know that the game\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s stars were on board. And they were. But, they all advocated for a format they were familiar with: 72-hole stroke play.  >Don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t blame the players. Although that might be their preference, the IOC has long held that Olympic sports should adhere to a format used to determine the winners of other high-end competitions. Hence, the same format we see constantly. How much the IGF has lobbied them on other format is unclear.  Also, the IOC is obsessed by capping the field size due to lack of space in the Olympic Village for athletes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094even though virtually no golfers, especially the elite of the elite, will stay there. Going to at least 78 players\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094which is more than manageable for a no-cut event, seems far more prudent, especially when the venue is nowhere near the Olympic Village. A majority if not all of the players are staying in private accommodations or hotels.  > Then there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the qualification system. From the start, the IGF went with OWGR, stipulating that the top 15 individuals in the OWGR at a cut-off point that included a two-year qualification period would automatically qualify, with no more than four per country and no more than two per country beyond that.  That is why just 10 of the top 15 players in the current OWGR are in the field, including all of the top seven.  That system has been used for all three of the competitions since golf returned to the Games in 2016 without much incident. The qualifying period for the 2024 Olympic golf began the week after the U.S. Open won by Matt Fitzpatrick.  LIV Golf had played one event to that point.  The obvious omission from this week\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s tournament is Bryson DeChambeau, who was well outside the top 200 in the OWGR before tying for sixth at the Masters, finishing second to Xander Schauffele at the PGA Championship and then winning the U.S. Open\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094in the final qualifying week.  DeChambeau moved up to 10th\\u00c2\\u00a0in the OWGR after his victory but that only left him as the sixth American behind Scottie Scheffler, Schauffele, Wyndham Clark, Collin Morikawa and Patrick Cantlay. In the past two years, DeChambeau has played in just 10 qualifying events.  Had he been earning any level of points via LIV Golf, he quite likely would be among the top four Americans and competing for a gold medal this week.  Understandably, this has caused a good bit of angst and led to conjecture that the qualifying process be changed.  \\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think it would be great if the countries can get to pick who they bring and just be like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098hey, these are the guys that we believe have a chance to win a medal,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 or \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098this is the guys that I want to bring,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Ancer said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cMaybe that would be a way to fix it. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not going to be easy. Not everybody is going to be happy.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  No doubt. But it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s true that other Olympic sports have qualification criteria that vary by country.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think you can always do it, like with other sports, and allow the countries to pick themselves,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Jon Rahm said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThere needs to be some guidelines, but like Team USA Basketball has freedom to choose whoever they want.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI understand it's a different circumstance, but I think you need to let each country choose who they want to play.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Shane Lowry noted that \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cNo. 9 in the world is not here, either, for the Americans. The American team is a hard team to make.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Lowry was speaking of Patrick Cantlay, the fifth American who is a top-10 player in the world but not worthy of the Olympics because the U.S. can only bring four players.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think that's the nature of qualification for the Olympics,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Rory McIlroy said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI mean, you could have the fifth-best sprinter in the world but if he's from a certain country, he's not able to make it.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo I think it's just the way that the qualification works in the Olympic Games, and that's not just in golf. That's in other disciplines, as well.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Without the ranking system, there is some question as to how the field would be filled. How many from each country? Which countries? Could there be qualifying events to determine Olympic players outside of a certain ranking structure?  All of that gets complicated and McIlroy leaned into the OWGR system even if it impacts LIV Golf players.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI do not think there is any other way to do it because it's hard to compare the golf that they play to the golf that we play,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d McIlroy said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat's the reason they did not get World Ranking points, right.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo if you want to qualify for the Olympics, you knew what you had to do. Just like if you wanted to qualify for the Ryder Cup, you knew what you had to do. They were very aware of the decision they made when they did.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Ortiz acknowledged the decisions made. That doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t make the situation any easier. In one regard, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s fortunate to be from a country that doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t have numerous high-level golfers.  He is currently ranked 272nd\\u00c2\\u00a0in the world but had fallen outside of the top 1,000 when he won the Oman International Series event in February. That moved him up high enough to still qualify for the Olympics.  Ortiz took up the LIV Golf mantle when seeking a remedy.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe solution would be people up there to leave their egos on the side and find a common ground,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think there is definitely common ground\\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 and both sides have to give something up to find common ground. I believe both of us (Ortiz and Ancer) should be playing majors. I think we played great golf this year, and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hard to get in them. I tried to qualify for the British Open. I just barely missed. But you know, there should be a way for us to get in there, a simpler way.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  When the tournament begins Thursday, four players will be making their third appearance in the Olympics: New Zealand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Ryan Fox, Malaysia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Gavin Green, Chinese Taipei\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s C.T. Pan and Paraguay\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Fabrizio Zanotti.  There are 32 countries represented in the 60-player field, which is down from the 32 in 2021 and the 36 in 2016.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Bob Harig is a senior writer covering golf for Sports Illustrated. He has more than 25 years experience on the beat, including 15 at ESPN. Harig is a regular guest on Sirius XM PGA Tour Radio and has written two books, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDRIVE: The Lasting Legacy of Tiger Woods\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTiger and Phil: Golf\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Most Fascinating Rivalry.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He graduated from Indiana University where he earned an Evans Scholarship, named in honor of the great amateur golfer Charles (Chick) Evans Jr. Harig, a former president of the Golf Writers Association of America, lives in Clearwater, Fla.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"